equation_narrative.headline: Model selects lysine over arginine despite strong positive charge context
equation_narrative.story: Position 54 sits in a charged surface context with 5 structural contacts and 2 co-evolving positions. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation consistent with polar and charged residues, reading structural contacts that establish a positively-charged environment. The logit lens shows early volatility across multiple polar/charged candidates (S, Y, T, Q) as different aspects of the context are integrated. At layer 28, lysine surges to dominance (31.4%) and continues rising to 75.6% by layer 33, driven by strong MLP support in layers 27-32. The model correctly identifies the need for a positive charge but selects the shorter, more flexible lysine over the correct arginine.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 show the model reading a charged surface environment. Early attention features (F1:5480, F1:9146, F1:1508 all ~45 proj) encode the local sequence context around QLEDG[R]TLSDY. By layer 9, attention features (F9:5728 at 50.1 proj, F9:1281 at 46.0 proj) integrate structural information from 5 nearby contacts. The logit lens shows high volatility with 13 lead changes across S, Y, L, T, Q, A candidates—reflecting the model's exploration of different aspects of the polar/charged context rather than prediction attempts. MLP activity in layers 12-21 provides modest support for R (neurons N12:3609 at +0.203, N18:3625 at +0.338, N19:2010 at +0.537) while also supporting polar candidates like Q. By layer 23, the representation has stabilized around a charged/polar character with S leading at 17.2%, but the decision machinery has not yet engaged.
perception_phase.context_character: The assembled context by L23 is a charged, surface-exposed environment with strong polar character. The 5 structural contacts and 2 co-evolving positions establish constraints favoring positively charged or polar residues, consistent with ubiquitin's surface chemistry at this position.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 5 residues read via attention heads in layers 8-18, establishing charged surface environment
Co-evolutionary signal: 2 coupled positions provide weak but consistent support for positive charge
L9 attention features: F9:5728 (50.1 proj), F9:1281 (46.0 proj) integrate 3D structural context
L18-19 MLP neurons: N18:3625 (+0.338 for R), N19:2010 (+0.537 for R) provide early arginine support
Local sequence: QLEDG context with adjacent acidic residues (E, D) suggests charge complementarity

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at layer 28 when lysine surges from 4.2% to 31.4%, driven by massive MLP support (layer 27 MLP delta +4.73). Layers 29-32 see intense competition: Q briefly peaks at 22.3% (L29) before collapsing, while K continues rising. Key lysine-supporting neurons activate in L29-32: N29:1348 (+0.571 proj), N31:307 (+0.880 proj), N32:4772 (+0.801 proj). Attention heads in L31-32 (head 8 at +2.825 proj, head 9 at +2.515 proj) read structural contacts and strongly reinforce K. Arginine receives consistent but weaker support throughout, peaking at only 10.2% by L33.
decision_phase.transition: At layers 23-25, the representation shifts from context encoding to amino acid prediction. Layer 24 shows the first strong AA-specific features (F24:7582 at 24.1 proj) and 18 lead changes compress into just 6 layers. The MLP at L25 applies a large negative correction (-4.06 delta), suppressing earlier polar candidates and clearing space for the K-specific prediction channels that activate at L27-28.

candidates.narrative: Lysine emerges decisively at layer 28, jumping from 4.2% to 31.4% and ultimately reaching 75.6%. This surge is driven by coordinated MLP and attention support: L27 MLP contributes +4.73 delta (neurons N27:722 at +0.658, N27:4618 at +0.437), followed by strong structural attention at L31-32 (heads 8 and 9 contributing +2.825 and +2.515 respectively). Late-layer MLP neurons N29:1348, N31:307, and N32:4772 provide sustained K-specific support. The model's preference for K over R likely reflects the shorter sidechain's compatibility with the local geometry.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L28 (31.4%), dominant by L30 (52.7%), final 75.6%
key_evidence: N27:722 (MLP, +0.658 proj) — R/K-supporting neuron, fires at decision transition
L31 attention head 8 (+2.825 proj) — structural writer strongly supporting K
L27 MLP velocity: +4.73 delta, largest positive shift in decision phase

candidates.narrative: Arginine is the true residue but never exceeds 10.2% probability. It receives consistent support throughout perception (N12:3609 at +0.203, N18:3625 at +0.338, N19:2010 at +0.537) and decision phases (N21:2856 at +0.525, N22:292 at +0.599, N28:4625 at +0.579), but this support is always weaker than K's. The model correctly identifies the need for positive charge but underweights the specific structural requirements that distinguish R's longer, more rigid guanidinium group from K's shorter, flexible amine. Late-layer features F30:4107 (40.8 proj) and F33:6423 (115.8 proj) support both K and R but favor K more strongly.
candidates.key_layers: Steady 2-5% through L23, rises to 10.2% by L33

N22:292 (MLP, +0.599 proj) — late perception R writer
N28:4625 (MLP, +0.579 proj) — decision-phase R support, but outcompeted by K neurons
Consistent but insufficient: R neurons fire throughout but never achieve K's coordination

candidates.narrative: Glutamine shows strong early representation character (11.0% at L8, leading at L7 with 21.1%) and briefly resurges in the decision phase, peaking at 22.3% at L29 before collapsing to 2.6%. The early prominence reflects Q's polar character matching the initial context assembly. The L29 peak is driven by MLP neurons supporting polar candidates before K-specific channels fully activate. The rapid collapse after L29 (from 22.3% to 2.6%) occurs as attention heads at L31-32 strongly favor K over Q, and MLP neurons like N29:2016 (-0.959 proj) actively suppress non-basic residues.
candidates.key_layers: Early leader L7-8 (21.1%), resurges L29 (22.3%), collapses to 2.6%

L29 peak at 22.3%: brief competition before K dominance

candidates.narrative: Histidine maintains steady support as the third positive charge option, finishing at 7.6%. It peaks very early (12.5% at L1) when the representation reflects general positive charge character, then stabilizes at 3-8% through the decision phase. Late features like F30:4107 and F33:6423 provide modest H support alongside K and R. The model considers H as a weaker alternative to K/R, consistent with histidine's intermediate pKa and smaller sidechain making it less suitable for this strongly basic position.
candidates.key_layers: Early peak L1 (12.5%), stable 3-8% through decision
key_evidence: F1 early peak: representation consistent with positive charge before specificity emerges
F30:4107 (attn, 40.8 proj) — supports all three positive candidates but favors K
Steady baseline: H maintained as fallback positive charge option

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from hydrophobic/aromatic character (Y, L leading at L3-6) to polar/charged character as attention begins integrating structural contacts. Q takes the lead at L7 (21.1%), and K first appears competitively at L8 (21.4%). This marks the transition from reading local sequence to incorporating 3D structural information. Features F9:5728 and F9:1281 (both >43 proj) encode the structural context that establishes the charged environment.

The perception-to-decision transition occurs here. Layer 23 shows the last of 13 lead changes in the perception phase (S at 17.2%). Layer 24 introduces AA-specific prediction features (F24:7582 at 24.1 proj), and L25 MLP applies a massive -4.06 delta that suppresses polar candidates and clears the field. This negative correction removes Q, N, and S from contention, setting up the K vs R competition that dominates L27-33.

Lysine's decisive emergence. Layer 27 MLP delivers +4.73 delta (largest positive velocity event), driven by neurons N27:722 (+0.658) and N27:4618 (+0.437) that strongly favor K over R. K jumps from 4.2% to 31.4% at L28. This is the moment the model commits to lysine as the answer, with subsequent layers reinforcing rather than reconsidering this choice. The coordination between MLP neurons and structural attention heads at L27-28 represents the model's final integration of geometry and chemistry.

deep_dives.label: Early attention features L1-9
deep_dives.caption: These features encode the initial context assembly: local sequence patterns (F1:5480, F1:9146) and early structural integration (F9:5728, F9:1281). High projection values (40-50) indicate strong activation, but at these layers they represent context encoding, not prediction.

deep_dives.label: Perception MLP L12-21
deep_dives.caption: MLP neurons in the perception phase provide early evidence for R (N12:3609, N18:3625, N19:2010) and Q (various neurons), but with modest strength (+0.2 to +0.5 proj). The model is gathering evidence, not yet deciding. Note the mix of R-supporting and Q-supporting neurons reflecting the ambiguity in the assembled context.

deep_dives.label: Decision transition L23-25
deep_dives.caption: Layer 24 features mark the shift to prediction mode. F24:7582 (24.1 proj) is the first strong AA-specific feature. The L25 MLP's -4.06 delta clears away polar candidates, setting up the K vs R competition.

deep_dives.label: K emergence L27-29 MLP
deep_dives.caption: The decisive MLP activity that selects lysine. L27 neurons N27:722 and N27:4618 initiate the surge (+4.73 total delta). L28-29 neurons N28:4625, N29:1348, N29:4998 sustain it. Compare the strength of K-supporting neurons to the weaker R-supporting neurons active at the same layers.

deep_dives.label: Structural attention L31-32
deep_dives.caption: Attention heads 8 and 9 at L31-32 are structural writers (>68% structural attention) that strongly favor K (+2.825 and +2.515 proj). They read the 3D contacts and reinforce the K decision. Head 3 at L32 is a local eraser (-2.839 proj) that suppresses alternatives.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction features L30-33
deep_dives.caption: High-projection features (>100 at L33) that encode the final K prediction. F30:6682 (40.9 proj MLP) and F33:6423 (115.8 proj attention) are K-specific prediction channels. These features have high enrichment for K and represent the model's committed answer.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly identifies position 54 as requiring a positive charge, assembling a charged surface context through structural contacts and co-evolutionary signals in layers 1-23. However, at the decision phase (L27-28), lysine-specific MLP neurons and structural attention heads coordinate to select K over R, likely because the local geometry favors K's shorter, more flexible sidechain. The decisive evidence is the L27 MLP surge (+4.73 delta) and L31-32 structural attention (+5.3 combined proj) that strongly favor K. Arginine receives consistent but weaker support throughout, never achieving the coordinated activation that K demonstrates. The model's error reflects a subtle geometric preference rather than a failure to recognize the charged environment.
